I have written `hypothesis.md` and `candidate.py` for a new, single-mechanism cognitive hypothesis: that people judge randomness using the length of the maximum unbroken streak (run) in the sequence. 

I checked that it avoids any mixing of cues (e.g. no use of alternation rate or head proportion) and directly maps the `max_run_a` and `max_run_b` columns to a PyMC model using a strictly negative relationship against the streak length. I also added numerical clamping for the sigmoid outputs to guarantee that the `p_left` log-likelihoods remain completely stable as requested. Finally, the self-check tests pass locally.
